  Figma recently introduced slots in components, which let you define swappable content regions inside a base component. For Modal and Sheet, this means:  
                  
  Current state: You likely have separate Modal/Sheet variants for each use case (or raw frames duplicated per screen), which means updating shared chrome 
  (header bar, close button, footer buttons, overlay) requires touching every instance.
                                                                                                                                                           
  With slots, the approach would be:                                                                                                                       
  
  - Base Modal component — fixed chrome (overlay, container, header with title + close, footer with action buttons), with a body slot that accepts any     
  content         
  - Base Sheet component — same idea (slide-in panel, header, footer), body slot swappable                                                                 
  - Content for each use case (e.g. "Create Share Class form", "Confirm Action", "Filter Panel") lives as separate slot content components that plug into  
  the body                                                                                                                                                 
                                                                                                                                                           
  The key trade-off:                                                                                                                                       
                  
  - A) Slots approach — One base component, swap body content per instance. Clean, DRY, easy to update chrome globally. But requires discipline — every    
  body variant needs to be a separate component.
  - B) Variant approach — Multiple variants in a component set (one per use case). Simpler to browse in the assets panel, but chrome updates require       
  touching every variant.                                                                                                                                  
  - C) Hybrid — Base with slots for custom content, plus a few pre-built "preset" variants for common patterns (confirmation dialog, form sheet).
                                                                                                                                                           
  I'd recommend A (pure slots) since you're building a product demo with many different modal/sheet contents — it keeps the base components lean and lets  
  you compose freely.                                                                                                                                      
                                                                                                                                                           
  What's your thinking — do any of these match what you had in mind, or do you want to explore a different direction?                                      
   
